        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Google Pigeon Update</strong> was a July 2014 algorithm change that bridged local and organic search. Before Pigeon, local rankings ran on their own signals independent of organic SEO. After Pigeon, <strong>domain authority, backlinks, and content quality directly influenced local pack placement</strong> — making organic SEO investment essential for local visibility.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Released</div>
            <div class="tms-value">July 2014</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO Algorithm</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Organic signals in local</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If your local rankings plateaued even after perfecting your Google Business Profile, Pigeon is likely why. Organic SEO — content, backlinks, domain authority — now feeds directly into whether you appear in the local pack.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Google Pigeon Update?</h2>
        <p>The Google Pigeon Update was Google's first major step toward treating local and organic search as a unified system rather than two separate ranking engines. Named by the SEO industry (Google never officially named it), Pigeon deployed in July 2014 for US English results and rolled out globally through late 2014.</p>
        <p>Three changes defined the update:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Organic signal integration</strong> — domain authority, backlink profile, on-page SEO, and content quality became factors in local pack rankings</li>
          <li><strong>Distance refinements</strong> — Google improved its location calculations, making results more accurately calibrated to searcher position</li>
          <li><strong>Directory site elevation</strong> — platforms like Yelp, TripAdvisor, and Urbanspoon gained prominent local placement because their high domain authority now carried weight</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why it matters now</div>
          <p>Pigeon's principles are not a separate filter — they are permanently baked into Google's local algorithm. Every local ranking decision Google makes today still weighs the organic signals Pigeon introduced in 2014.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why does the Google Pigeon Update matter for local businesses?</h2>
        <p>Before Pigeon, you could dominate local results with GBP optimization alone. After Pigeon, a competitor with a stronger website consistently outranks a better-optimized GBP. There are four specific ways this changes your strategy:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Website quality now affects local pack position.</strong> A business with 40+ quality backlinks and regular content beats a bare-bones website with a perfect GBP, all else equal.</li>
          <li><strong>Organic SEO investment compounds locally.</strong> Every blog post you publish, every backlink you earn — they improve both organic and local rankings simultaneously.</li>
          <li><strong>Directory sites compete directly.</strong> Yelp, TripAdvisor, and Houzz may outrank your own listing for branded or category searches, especially in competitive markets.</li>
          <li><strong>Accurate distance calculation changed who wins nearby searches.</strong> Businesses that relied on city-wide rankings saw variability as results became tied to searcher coordinates.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How does the Google Pigeon Update work?</h2>
        <p>Pigeon works by feeding the same organic ranking signals Google uses for standard web results into the local ranking algorithm. When someone searches "best plumber near me," Google doesn't just check proximity and GBP completeness — it also checks which plumber websites have the strongest domain authority and most relevant content.</p>
        <p>The mechanism operates in three layers:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Signal weighting.</strong> Organic signals — domain authority, referring domains, on-page optimisation — get weighted alongside local signals like proximity, reviews, and GBP completeness.</li>
          <li><strong>Distance recalibration.</strong> Google refined how it interprets "near me" searches, shrinking the radius for tight-query terms and expanding it for service-area businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Perpetual integration.</strong> Subsequent updates (Possum 2016, Vicinity 2021) built on Pigeon's foundation. There was no "undo" — organic signals have been a local ranking factor ever since.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Google Pigeon Update vs later local algorithm updates</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Update</th><th>Year</th><th>Primary change</th><th>Effect on local rankings</th></tr>
            </thead>
