              <tr><td><strong>Vicinity</strong></td><td>2021</td><td>Proximity reweighted heavily</td><td>Physical closeness became dominant local signal</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Pigeon Update examples</h2>
        <p>Here is what the Pigeon effect looks like in practice:</p>
        <h3>Example 1 — Directory sites jumping to page 1</h3>
        <p>A Yelp restaurant listing with thousands of reviews and strong domain authority jumped from page 3 to the first organic result for "best Italian restaurant [city]" post-Pigeon. The restaurant itself — with a lower-authority website — appeared further down even with a fully optimised GBP.</p>
        <h3>Example 2 — GBP-only businesses losing position</h3>
        <p>A local plumber with a minimal website and a well-optimised GBP lost local pack positions to a competitor publishing weekly blog content and holding 40+ referring domains. Same service area, same review count — the organic authority gap decided the outcome.</p>
        <h3>Example 3 — Content investment paying off locally</h3>
        <p>A dental clinic publishing 4 articles per month on oral health topics accumulated 60+ referring domains over 18 months. Their local pack position improved from position 4 to position 1 without any additional GBP optimisation — purely from organic authority growth feeding into local rankings via Pigeon's mechanism.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Google Pigeon Update vs Google Possum Update — what changed each time</h2>
        <p>Both updates reshaped local SEO, but they solved different problems.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Google Pigeon (2014)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Made organic signals influence local rankings</li>
              <li>Elevated directories with high domain authority</li>
              <li>Linked local and organic SEO permanently</li>
              <li>Distance calculation improvements</li>
              <li>Affected what ranks in local results</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Google Possum (2016)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Made results vary by searcher's exact location</li>
              <li>Added address-based filtering for co-located businesses</li>
              <li>Suburban businesses gained on downtown competitors</li>
              <li>Geo-grid tracking became essential</li>
              <li>Affected where rankings are seen, not just what ranks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices after the Google Pigeon Update</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Treat local and organic SEO as one strategy.</strong> Every blog post, backlink, and technical fix improves both. Stop separating them into different budgets.</li>
          <li><strong>Build domain authority steadily.</strong> Target 2-4 quality backlinks per month from local directories, industry publications, and chamber of commerce listings. Velocity matters more than bursts.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish location-relevant content.</strong> Blog posts covering local topics, neighbourhood guides, and service-area pages signal relevance to Google beyond just your GBP category.</li>
          <li><strong>Claim and optimise on high-DA directories.</strong> Yelp, TripAdvisor, Houzz, Angi — wherever your industry has authoritative directories, claim and optimise your listing. They rank in the local results and also link to your site.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix technical SEO on your website.</strong> Core Web Vitals, mobile-friendliness, and crawlability now influence your local pack position. A slow site loses local rankings too.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor rankings across organic and local simultaneously.</strong> Tools like BrightLocal, Whitespark, or Moz Local show local pack position. Pair with organic rank tracking to see both move together.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — GBP-only optimisation</div>
          <p>Many local businesses spend all their SEO budget on GBP management and zero on their website. Post-Pigeon, this is a losing strategy. A competitor with a website generating 20+ quality backlinks will beat your GBP-only approach even if your GBP profile is technically perfect.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes businesses make after the Pigeon Update</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring website authority.</strong> Focusing entirely on GBP and reviews while the competitor next door quietly builds a content library and earns backlinks.</li>
          <li><strong>Not claiming directory listings.</strong> Directories outrank individual businesses in post-Pigeon results — if you're not claimed and optimised on Yelp, you're losing that real estate twice.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing low-quality content.</strong> Publishing thin blog posts just to "have content" doesn't build authority. Google needs content that earns links and satisfies search intent.</li>
          <li><strong>Tracking only one location.</strong> Pigeon improved distance calculations, so your rank at the business address differs from your rank across your service area. Use geo-grid tools.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating local and organic as separate teams.</strong> The work is unified. The Pigeon Update made that permanent in 2014.</li>
        </ul>

